<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="45" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">
Holotype of this species was diagnosed as male in the original description without being dissected (
<bibRefCitation author="Chen, SH" journalOrPublisher="Notes d'Entomologie Chinoise" pageId="13" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 67" title="Galerucinae nouveaux de la Faune Chinoise." volume="9" year="1942">Chen 1942</bibRefCitation>
). Actually the holotype is female. Its spermatheca is illustrated here (Fig. 42). The updated catalogue of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Galerucinae">Galerucinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Beenen 2010</bibRefCitation>
) 
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="45" start="start">showed</pageBreakToken>
that this species belonged to a subgenus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Neogalerucella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Neogalerucella" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Neogalerucella</taxonomicName>
of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Galerucella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Galerucella" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Galerucella</taxonomicName>
. In this study, we found that the disc of pronotum is entirely covered by hairs. So we think that this species should be remained in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Pyrrhalta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pyrrhalta" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pyrrhalta</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
